Low Level Design for Luminary Page 5
1. Introduction
Education has always been a cornerstone of human progress, shaping minds and fostering
growth. In the modern age, the integration of advanced technologies into educational frameworks
is transforming how students learn and engage with materials. However, ensuring that these
technologies deliver an optimized and personalized learning experience remains a key challenge
for educators and technologists alike.
The Luminary Project is an innovative educational platform designed to address these challenges
by enhancing the learning experience for high school students. By leveraging technologies such
as Generative AI and gamification, Luminary seeks to improve educational outcomes through
personalized learning paths, real-time performance analysis, and interactive, engaging features.
The platform not only supports academic growth but also encourages motivation and active
participation from students.
The document provides a comprehensive overview of the Luminary platform's architectural
design. It outlines object design trade-offs, subsystem functionalities, and interface
documentation. The document encompasses engineering standards, definitions, acronyms,
abbreviations, and details on package and class interfaces.
1.1. Object Design Trade-offs
The design of the Luminary platform includes several trade-offs:
1.1.1. Reliability of Language Model Responses
A key consideration in developing the Luminary platform is the use of Generative AI to support
features like quiz generation, personalized recommendations, and content analysis. Since the
platform will primarily target Turkish users, the challenge lies in the limited availability of large
language models (LLMs) with strong support for Turkish. To address this, we plan to integrate
multiple LLMs, leveraging those that support both Turkish and other languages. This multi-LLM
approach ensures broader language coverage but introduces a trade-off in terms of reliability of
responses. Response times and accuracy may vary between models, and the need for seamless
switching between LLMs could increase the system’s complexity.
1.1.2. Resource Trade-offs for the Map Component
The Turkey Map subsystem, used to visualize educational success rates across different regions,
is resource-intensive due to the complex data visualization and real-time interaction
requirements. This subsystem is designed to be dynamic, allowing users to filter and drill down
into various metrics. However, the trade-off here involves balancing resource consumption and
response time. While advanced graphics and real-time data updates provide an enhanced user
experience, they also consume significant server resources, requiring careful allocation of
computational power.
Low Level Design for Luminary Page 6
1.1.3. Scalability vs. Complexity
In an effort to make the system scalable, the Luminary platform employs a microservices
architecture. This architectural style breaks the platform into small, independently deployable
services. For example, one service is dedicated to handling user data, another to generating AI-
based quizzes, and yet another for analytics. This separation ensures that each component can
scale independently (e.g., scaling only the quiz generation service during exam periods).
However, this introduces additional complexity, as the system must coordinate multiple services,
manage their communication, and handle the increased difficulty of deployment and
maintenance. The challenge lies in ensuring seamless integration while maintaining the
flexibility to scale specific components when needed.
1.1.4. Security vs. Usability
Security is paramount, especially with sensitive data being processed by the User Management
and Analysis subsystems. We have implemented JSON Web Tokens (JWT) to securely handle
authentication and authorization, while also securing key endpoints through encryption.
However, this security introduces some usability trade-offs.

'ClassName'. Variables and methods are formatted using camel case, such as 'variableName' and
'methodName()'. The table template below is utilized to represent the class interfaces:

1.3. Engineering Standards
The Luminary Project will adhere to industry-standard software engineering standards, including
modular design principles, secure coding guidelines, and scalable architecture frameworks. The
project will follow IEEE and ISO standards for software quality, data security, and user interface
design, ensuring maintainability, interoperability, and compliance with data protection
regulations.

2.Packages
2.1. Client Side
Figure 1: Client Package
2.1.1. LoginScreen
The LoginScreen acts as a entry point for users of the Luminary application. This screen is
designed with three Angular components, each responsible for a specific functionality:
•
LoginComponent
◦
The LoginComponent facilitates user authentication by providing a form where
users can input their registered email address and password. Upon clicking the
Login button, the component communicates with the backend service to validate
the entered credentials. If the authentication is successful, the user is redirected to
the HomeScreen. If the credentials are invalid, the component displays an
appropriate error message, prompting users to re-enter their information. This
component ensures a seamless and secure login process while maintaining user
experience through responsive design and feedback mechanisms.
Low Level Design for Luminary Page 9
•
RegistrationComponent
◦
The RegistrationComponent enables new users to create an account within the
Luminary application. When users click the Registration button, they are
presented with a form to enter the following information:
▪
Email Address: A valid email for account verification and notifications.
▪
Username: A unique identifier for the user within the application.
▪
High School Name: The name of the user’s high school for demographic
purposes.
▪
Password: A secure password that adheres to defined complexity
requirements.
◦
Upon submission, this component validates the input data and interacts with the
backend to create a new user account. If successful, a confirmation email is
dispatched to the provided address, ensuring users can verify their registration.
Error messages and form validations are integrated to enhance the user experience
and ensure data integrity.
•
ForgotPasswordComponent
◦
The ForgotPasswordComponent provides users with the ability to recover their
passwords if they have forgotten them. When the Forgot Password button is
clicked, this component prompts users to enter their registered email address.
After submission, the component communicates with the backend service to
generate a secure password reset link, which is sent to the user’s email. Users can
follow this link to create a new password, effectively restoring access to their
accounts. The component incorporates user-friendly feedback mechanisms to
guide users through the recovery process.
2.1.2. DashboardScreen
The dashboard serves as the central hub for users, providing a consolidated view of key features
and functionalities. Users can easily navigate to components like Analyze, Daily Study, History,
MyTasks, and Map. The Dashboard is designed with user experience in mind, offering intuitive
access to essential tools and resources, thereby enabling efficient academic exploration and task
management.
2.1.3. ProfileScreen
The ProfileScreen empowers users to manage their personal information and preferences within
the Luminary platform. Upon accessing this screen, users can view their profile details and make
updates, such as changing their password or adjusting their preferences. The screen includes
options for toggling between light and dark modes and a logout button for secure sign-out. This
functionality enhances user control and personalization.
2.1.4. AnalyzeScreen
The AnalyzeScreen offers comprehensive tools for assessing and enhancing student performance.
Users can upload questions they've answered incorrectly, select practice questions based on
difficulty, and visualize their performance through charts and graphs. This screen aims to foster
continuous improvement by providing personalized feedback and next steps based on user
performance data.
Low Level Design for Luminary Page 10
2.1.5. DailyStudyScreen
The DailyStudyScreen provides a structured environment for users to engage in their daily study
routines. Users can upload study materials, access MEB books, and utilize AI-powered tools for
summarization and question answering. This screen supports organized study sessions and
facilitates effective academic exploration, tailored to users' needs.
2.1.6. SmartStudyEnvironment
Within the SmartStudyEnvironment, users interact with an AI-driven interface for document
summarization and question answering. This dynamic environment enhances the study
experience by helping users focus on key information and clarifying complex topics.
2.1.7. MEBCheckInEnvironment
The MEBCheckInEnvironment allows students to access official MEB books and relevant
educational content. Through an intuitive chatbot interface, students can ask questions about
specific topics, and the system provides detailed explanations aligned with the curriculum,
supporting their learning needs effectively.
2.1.8. HistoryScreen
The HistoryScreen enables users to track their study progress and review past activities. Users
can categorize previously uploaded questions based on courses and topics, providing insights
into their performance and study patterns. This functionality supports informed decision-making
and personalized learning strategies.
2.1.9. MyTasksScreen
The MyTasksScreen offers a centralized platform for users to manage academic tasks and
assignments. Users can view tasks categorized by status (To-Do, In-Progress, Done), add
descriptions, and utilize drag-and-drop functionality for seamless organization. This screen
enhances task management and helps users stay organized with their academic responsibilities.
2.1.10. MapScreen
The MapScreen provides a visual representation of educational challenges across different
regions. Users can interact with a map where cities are color-coded based on the most
challenging courses in those areas. This screen offers valuable insights into regional educational
trends, facilitating targeted support initiatives to address academic challenges.

2.2. Microservices Side
Figure 2: Microservices Package
Low Level Design for Luminary Page 12
2.2.1. User Auth Service
The User Auth Service microservice is responsible for managing user-related functionalities,
including user registration, authentication, and profile management. It enables users to create
accounts with unique usernames and emails while securely storing their passwords using
encryption. The service handles login operations by verifying user credentials and generating
authentication tokens for secure sessions. Additionally, it facilitates profile updates and password
management, ensuring data integrity and user privacy. By integrating robust security measures
and allowing seamless communication with other microservices, this microservice enhances the
overall user experience within the application.
2.2.2. Analyze Management
The Analyze Management Microservice is designed to enhance student performance by
providing comprehensive tools for evaluating their readiness for university entrance exams. This
microservice allows users to upload incorrect answers, select the number and difficulty level of
practice questions, and visualize their areas of weakness through graphical representations. The
system employs AI-generated questions based on user preferences, ensuring a tailored practice
experience.
The microservice facilitates the identification of topics where students struggle and provides
detailed feedback on their performance. This enables students to track their improvement over
time. Implementing HTTP REST APIs for seamless communication, the service can interact with
a PostgreSQL database to store user data and performance metrics. Future enhancements may
include integrating Kafka for efficient data processing and messaging, particularly to manage
user interactions and real-time feedback. Furthermore, LLM API integration is planned to
generate practice questions, fostering an adaptive learning environment that encourages
continuous improvement and personalized education pathways.
2.2.3. Map Management
The Map Management Microservice provides a dynamic visual representation of educational
challenges across various regions of Turkey. This microservice displays a clickable and
hoverable map where cities are color-coded based on the courses that present the most significant
challenges. Users can easily navigate through the map and click on specific cities to access
detailed insights regarding the challenging courses in those locations, including relevant statistics
and percentages.
Leveraging REST API calls, the microservice ensures real-time data retrieval and user
interaction. It integrates with a PostgreSQL database to store geographical and educational data,
which can be updated periodically. Additionally, to enhance the performance and scalability of
the service, Kafka may be utilized for asynchronous communication between microservices,
allowing for efficient data updates and real-time notifications to users. This microservice plays a
crucial role in providing targeted insights and support for addressing academic challenges across
different regions.
Low Level Design for Luminary Page 13
2.2.4. Smart Study Management
In this service, students can engage with a chatbot-like interface to request document
summarization, making lengthy study materials more digestible. Additionally, students can ask
questions related to their uploaded documents, receiving AI-supported answers that leverage
large language models to provide accurate and contextually relevant responses. A multilingual
LLM API that supports Turkish language will be used here. We will send a request to this API
end with the necessary information and an appropriate prompt and edit the result. We will deliver
the edited result to the user via a REST API endpoint.
2.2.5. Meb Study Management
The MEB Check-In Environment is designed to support students by providing easy access to
official MEB books and the educational content within them. Through a user-friendly chatbot
interface, students can enter topics they have questions about. The system scans the MEB books
using advanced AI technologies to locate the desired topics and provides detailed explanations
from the relevant sections of the books. Meb books will be stored in our These tasks will come
from our PostgreSQL database. We will send what the user wants to ask about the book to an
LLM API like the one we use in Smart Study Management Service.
2.2.6. History Management Service(will be implemented)
The History System enables users to monitor their study progress and track past activities within
the Luminary platform. Past activities will be kept in a user-specific table in the PostgreSQL
database. Users can review previously uploaded questions, categorize them based on courses,
and classify question topic titles for easy reference.
2.2.7. My Task Management Service(will be implemented)
The MyTasks System offers users a centralized platform to manage and track their academic
tasks and assignments. Users can view tasks categorized into "To-Do," "In-Progress," and
"Done" states, assign tasks to themselves, and add descriptions for clarity. These tasks will come
from our PostgreSQL database.
